# Next.js 16 Core

Cursor: when you generate Next.js code, follow these rules. Target `next@16.0+` on `react@19.2+`. The companion `nextjs-anti-patterns` rule rejects the inverse patterns.

## Imports and types

```typescript
// Server-side helpers (work in Server Components, Server Actions, Route Handlers)
import { cookies, headers, draftMode } from 'next/headers';

// Navigation (App Router only - NEVER from 'next/router')
import { redirect, notFound, permanentRedirect } from 'next/navigation';
import { useRouter, usePathname, useSearchParams } from 'next/navigation'; // client

// Page / layout / route prop types (after `next typegen` once)
import type { PageProps, LayoutProps, RouteContext } from 'next';

// Cache directives (stable since v16)
import { unstable_cache } from 'next/cache'; // legacy, prefer 'use cache' directive
import { revalidatePath, revalidateTag, updateTag } from 'next/cache';
import { cacheLife, cacheTag } from 'next/cache';

// React 19 hooks
import { useActionState, use, cache } from 'react';
import { useFormStatus } from 'react-dom'; // still here, only inside <form> children

// Taint APIs (still flagged experimental in v16 - alias on import)
import { experimental_taintUniqueValue as taintUniqueValue } from 'react';
import { experimental_taintObjectReference as taintObjectReference } from 'react';
```

> Never import `Page` types from `next/router` - that is the Pages Router namespace. App Router uses `next/navigation`.

## Server Components are the default

Every file in `app/` is a Server Component unless it (or one of its ancestors) declares `'use client'`. Server Components:

- Run on the server, never ship JS to the client
- Can be `async` and `await` data directly
- Cannot use React hooks (`useState`, `useEffect`, `useReducer`, ...) or browser APIs
- Cannot use React Context (`createContext` providers do not propagate to server children)

```typescript
// app/blog/page.tsx (Server Component)
import { getPosts } from '@/lib/dal/posts';

export default async function BlogIndex() {
  const posts = await getPosts(); // direct DAL call, runs on the server
  return (
    <ul>
      {posts.map(p => <li key={p.id}>{p.title}</li>)}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

## The `'use client'` boundary

A `'use client'` directive marks a file (and everything it imports transitively) as client-rendered. Push the boundary as far down the tree as possible. A `'use client'` on a layout makes the entire subtree client-rendered.

```typescript
// app/(dashboard)/layout.tsx (Server Component - no directive)
import { Sidebar } from './_components/sidebar';
export default function Layout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <div className="grid grid-cols-[200px_1fr]">
      <Sidebar />            {/* small Client Component */}
      <main>{children}</main> {/* Server Components flow through */}
    </div>
  );
}

// app/(dashboard)/_components/sidebar.tsx
'use client';
import { useState } from 'react';
export function Sidebar() {
  const [open, setOpen] = useState(true);
  /* ... */
}
```

A Server Component can render a Client Component, but the props passed must be serializable (no functions, no class instances, no Dates with circular refs).

## `server-only` and `client-only` import guards

When a module must never cross the boundary, mark it.

```typescript
// lib/dal/posts.ts
import 'server-only'; // throws at build time if a Client Component imports this

export async function getPosts() {
  const session = await verifySession();
  if (!session) return [];
  return db.post.findMany({ where: { authorId: session.userId } });
}
```

```typescript
// lib/browser/local-storage.ts
import 'client-only'; // throws at build time if a Server Component imports this

export function readPref(key: string) {
  return window.localStorage.getItem(key);
}
```

## Async request APIs (the v15+ rule, fully enforced in v16)

`cookies()`, `headers()`, `draftMode()`, `params`, `searchParams`, and the `id` in image-metadata callbacks are all Promises. There is no sync form.

```typescript
// Server Component / async function
import { cookies, headers } from 'next/headers';

export default async function Page({ params }: PageProps<'/blog/[slug]'>) {
  const { slug } = await params;
  const cookieStore = await cookies();
  const headerList = await headers();
  /* ... */
}

// Route Handler
export async function GET(req: Request, ctx: RouteContext<'/users/[id]'>) {
  const { id } = await ctx.params;
  /* ... */
}
```

Setting cookies is forbidden during render. Mutations live in Server Actions, Route Handlers, or `proxy.ts`.

## Data Access Layer (Vercel's official recommendation)

The DAL is a server-only module that centralizes data access AND authorization. Every Server Component, Server Action, and Route Handler goes through it.

```typescript
// lib/dal/index.ts
import 'server-only';
import { cache } from 'react';
import { cookies } from 'next/headers';
import { db } from '@/lib/db';

export const verifySession = cache(async () => {
  const cookieStore = await cookies();
  const token = cookieStore.get('session')?.value;
  if (!token) return null;
  const session = await db.session.findUnique({ where: { token } });
  if (!session || session.expiresAt < new Date()) return null;
  return { userId: session.userId, role: session.role };
});

// DTO-returning function with authz baked in
export async function getMyPosts() {
  const session = await verifySession();
  if (!session) return [];
  const posts = await db.post.findMany({ where: { authorId: session.userId } });
  return posts.map(p => ({ id: p.id, title: p.title, createdAt: p.createdAt.toISOString() }));
}
```

`cache()` from React memoizes `verifySession` per render pass - the underlying cookie lookup + DB query runs once even if 50 Server Components call it. See the dedicated `nextjs-data-access-layer` rule for the full pattern.

## Server Actions: validate, authorize, mutate, revalidate

```typescript
// app/posts/actions.ts
'use server';

import { z } from 'zod';
import { revalidateTag } from 'next/cache';
import { redirect } from 'next/navigation';
import { verifySession } from '@/lib/dal';
import { db } from '@/lib/db';

const CreatePostSchema = z.object({
  title: z.string().min(1).max(200),
  body: z.string().min(1).max(50_000),
});

type State = { errors?: Record<string, string[]>; ok?: boolean };

export async function createPost(_prev: State, formData: FormData): Promise<State> {
  const session = await verifySession();
  if (!session) return { errors: { _form: ['Sign in to post'] } };

  const parsed = CreatePostSchema.safeParse({
    title: formData.get('title'),
    body: formData.get('body'),
  });
  if (!parsed.success) return { errors: parsed.error.flatten().fieldErrors };

  try {
    await db.post.create({
      data: { ...parsed.data, authorId: session.userId },
    });
  } catch (e) {
    return { errors: { _form: ['Failed to save'] } };
  }

  revalidateTag('posts', 'max');
  redirect('/posts'); // OUTSIDE the try/catch
}
```

Bind on the client with `useActionState`:

```typescript
'use client';
import { useActionState } from 'react';
import { createPost } from './actions';

export function CreatePostForm() {
  const [state, formAction, pending] = useActionState(createPost, {});
  return (
    <form action={formAction}>
      <input name="title" />
      {state.errors?.title && <p>{state.errors.title[0]}</p>}
      <textarea name="body" />
      <SubmitButton pending={pending} />
    </form>
  );
}
```

## Cache Components: opt-in caching

With `cacheComponents: true` in `next.config.ts`, all dynamic code is dynamic by default. Cache explicitly with the `'use cache'` directive.

```typescript
// next.config.ts
const config = { cacheComponents: true };
export default config;

// lib/dal/prices.ts
import 'server-only';
import { cacheLife, cacheTag } from 'next/cache';

export async function getPrices() {
  'use cache';
  cacheLife('hours');
  cacheTag('prices');
  const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/prices');
  return res.json();
}
```

The `'use cache'` directive can be at function, component, or file level. `cacheLife` accepts named profiles (`'seconds'`, `'minutes'`, `'hours'`, `'days'`, `'weeks'`, `'max'`) or inline `{ stale, revalidate, expire }`.

Invalidation:

- `revalidateTag(tag, profile)` - clears cache, re-renders affected routes. Required 2-arg in v16.
- `updateTag(tag)` - inside a Server Action: expires AND refreshes within the same request (read-your-writes).
- `refresh()` - inside a Server Action: refreshes uncached data without touching cache.
- `revalidatePath(path)` - path-scoped invalidation, still supported.

## Route segment config

Per-segment opts via exports at the top of `page.tsx`, `layout.tsx`, or `route.ts`:

```typescript
export const runtime = 'nodejs' | 'edge';        // default: nodejs
export const dynamic = 'force-dynamic' | 'force-static' | 'error' | 'auto';
export const dynamicParams = true | false;
export const revalidate = 60 | false;            // ISR seconds, or false for static
export const fetchCache = 'default-cache' | 'force-cache' | 'force-no-store';
export const preferredRegion = 'auto' | 'global' | string[];
export const maxDuration = 60;                   // serverless function max seconds
```

With Cache Components enabled, prefer the `'use cache'` directive over `dynamic`/`fetchCache`/`revalidate` exports for new code.

## File conventions

```
app/
  layout.tsx           Root layout (must render <html><body>)
  page.tsx             Home page
  loading.tsx          Suspense fallback for this segment + children
  error.tsx            Error boundary for page + children (NOT for sibling layout)
  not-found.tsx        Rendered when notFound() is called
  global-error.tsx     Replaces root layout on top-level throws (must render <html><body>)
  template.tsx         Like layout but re-mounts on navigation
  default.tsx          Required slot fallback for parallel routes (build fails without it)
  route.ts             Route handler (GET/POST/etc.)
  middleware.ts        DEPRECATED in v16, renamed to proxy.ts at the root
  proxy.ts             Edge-of-the-app interceptor (runs on every matching request)
  robots.ts            Generates /robots.txt
  sitemap.ts           Generates /sitemap.xml
  manifest.ts          Generates /manifest.webmanifest
  opengraph-image.tsx  Generates /opengraph-image
  twitter-image.tsx    Generates /twitter-image
  icon.tsx             Generates favicons
```

## v16 deltas vs v15 (the items most likely to be missed by an LLM trained on v15)

- **`middleware.ts` → `proxy.ts`** at the root. Function name `middleware` → `proxy`. Runs on Node.js runtime only. `middleware.ts` still works for the Edge case but is deprecated.
- **`experimental.ppr`, `experimental.dynamicIO`, `experimental.useCache`** flags removed. All collapsed into top-level `cacheComponents: true`.
- **`revalidateTag(tag)`** single-arg is deprecated; depending on installed patch and TS settings it surfaces as either a TypeScript error or a runtime deprecation. Treat it as an error and always pass `revalidateTag(tag, profile)`.
- **`updateTag(tag)`** is new. Server Actions only. Read-your-writes within a request.
- **`refresh()`** is new. Server Actions only. Refresh uncached data.
- **Turbopack is the default bundler.** Custom `webpack` config in `next.config` breaks `next build` unless you run with `--webpack`.
- **`next lint` removed.** Run ESLint or Biome directly.
- **`images.domains` deprecated.** Use `images.remotePatterns`.
- **`images.quality`** is coerced to the nearest value in `images.qualities` (default `[75]`).
- **`images.minimumCacheTTL`** default raised from 60s to 14400s.
- **Parallel routes require `default.js`** in every slot - build fails without it.
- **`serverRuntimeConfig` / `publicRuntimeConfig`** removed. Read `process.env` directly.
- **AMP** support gone.
- **`scroll-behavior: smooth`** no longer auto-applied. Opt in with `data-scroll-behavior="smooth"` on `<html>`.
- **`generateImageMetadata` callback `id`** is now a Promise (was a string).
- **React 19.2 features** are usable: `<ViewTransition>`, `useEffectEvent`, `<Activity>`.
- **React Compiler** stable as opt-in: `reactCompiler: true` in `next.config.ts`.

## What an LLM trained on 2023 still gets wrong

| Pattern | Correct replacement |
|---|---|
| `getServerSideProps` / `getStaticProps` | async Server Component with direct await |
| `pages/api/*.ts` | `app/api/<path>/route.ts` |
| `'use client'` on layouts | push the directive down to the smallest interactive component |
| `useEffect(() => fetch(...))` for server data | async Server Component |
| `cookies().get(...)` sync | `(await cookies()).get(...)` |
| `params.id` direct | `const { id } = await params` |
| `useFormState` from `react-dom` | `useActionState` from `react` |
| `revalidateTag('foo')` | `revalidateTag('foo', 'max')` or `updateTag('foo')` |
| `middleware.ts` (new code) | `proxy.ts` |
| `experimental.ppr: true` | `cacheComponents: true` (top-level) |
| `next lint` script | `eslint .` directly |
| `images.domains: [...]` | `images.remotePatterns: [...]` |
| `next/legacy/image` | `next/image` |
| `serverRuntimeConfig` | `process.env.*` |
| `redirect()` inside `try/catch` | `redirect()` outside the try/catch |

## Version targeting

Rules in this plugin assume:

- `next` >= 16.0.0 (current stable as of 2026-05). Many patterns work back to 15.x with the noted deltas.
- `react` >= 19.2.0 (matches what Next.js 16 ships with).
- `typescript` >= 5.6.

If you are on 15.x and not ready to upgrade, use the `/nextjs-migrate-v15-to-v16` skill for the codemod sequence.
